Types disappear before runtime. So why is Angular built around them?
TypeScript does not exist at runtime.
Every interface, type alias, generic, and type annotation you write is removed before your application reaches the browser.
The browser only receives JavaScript.
So why did Angular build its entire development model around TypeScript?
The obvious answer is type safety.
TypeScript catches spelling mistakes, improves autocomplete, and makes refactoring safer.
All of that is valuable.
But Angular’s relationship with TypeScript goes deeper than better editor suggestions.
Angular chose TypeScript because it wanted a framework that could support large applications, strong tooling, predictable architecture, compile-time analysis, and long-term maintainability.
TypeScript was not simply added on top of Angular.
It helped shape how Angular works.
TypeScript disappears before the application runs
Consider this interface:
interface User {
id: string;
name: string;
email: string;
}It helps your editor understand what a User should look like.
It can warn you when a required property is missing.
It can catch this mistake:
const user: User = {
id: '101',
name: 'Pranav'
// email is missing
};But the interface does not exist in the final JavaScript.
After compilation, the browser has no knowledge of User.
This is why you cannot do this:
if (value instanceof User) {
// This will not work because User is only an interface
}Interfaces provide compile-time information, not runtime behaviour.
TypeScript can check what your code claims to be working with, but it does not automatically validate what an API actually returns.
That distinction is important:
TypeScript protects assumptions during development. Runtime validation protects application boundaries.
Why Angular needed TypeScript
Angular was designed for applications that may contain hundreds of components, services, routes, forms, and API integrations.
These applications are often maintained for years and worked on by multiple teams.
At that scale, small misunderstandings become expensive.
One developer expects an amount in rupees.
Another sends it in paise.
One service may return null.
Another part of the application assumes it will always receive an object.
A property gets renamed, but an old usage remains hidden inside a rarely visited screen.
JavaScript allows developers to build applications like this.
But TypeScript makes those applications easier to understand and safer to change.
It gives teams clear contracts between different parts of the application.
A service can define exactly what it accepts.
A component can describe what inputs it expects.
An API response can have an explicit shape.
A function can clearly communicate what it returns.
This becomes increasingly valuable as the codebase grows.
But types are only half the story
Angular also needs to understand the role of each class inside the framework.
A normal class is just a class:
export class UserComponent {}Nothing here tells Angular that the class should render something on the screen.
Angular needs additional information:
@Component({
selector: 'app-user',
templateUrl: './user.component.html'
})
export class UserComponent {}The @Component decorator provides metadata about the class.
It tells Angular:

• This class is a component.

• This is its selector.

• This is its template.

• This is how it should participate in the application.
The same idea applies to other Angular decorators:
@Injectable()
@Directive()
@Pipe()
@Input()
@Output()They describe how classes and properties should be treated by Angular.
A service marked with @Injectable can participate in dependency injection.
A class marked with @Component becomes part of the UI.
A property marked with @Input becomes part of a component’s public API.
The class contains your application logic.
The metadata explains how Angular should use it.
What happens during the build
A simplified Angular build process looks like this:
TypeScript source
↓
Type checking
↓
Angular compiler analyses templates and metadata
↓
Type information is removed
↓
JavaScript is generated
↓
Browser runs the applicationThe browser does not need to understand TypeScript.
It also does not need to analyse your original Angular source code in the same way your build tools do.
Angular’s compiler performs much of that work before the application reaches the browser.
This allows Angular to detect template problems, understand component relationships, generate rendering instructions, and prepare dependency-injection factories during the build.
That is why Angular’s connection with TypeScript is not limited to autocomplete.
TypeScript gives Angular a structured environment that its tooling and compiler can analyse.
A real example
Imagine a banking application with a money-transfer service:
interface TransferRequest {
fromAccountId: string;
toAccountId: string;
amountCents: number;
}interface TransferResult {
transactionId: string;
status: 'pending' | 'completed' | 'failed';
}@Injectable({
providedIn: 'root'
})
export class TransferService {
transfer(
request: TransferRequest
): Observable<TransferResult> {
return this.http.post<TransferResult>(
'/api/transfers',
request
);
}
}The types protect the contract during development.
A developer cannot accidentally send:
{
fromAccountId: 'A101',
toAccountId: 'B205',
amount: 100
}when the service expects amountCents.
That mismatch can be caught before the code reaches production.
Meanwhile, @Injectable tells Angular how the service should participate in dependency injection.
The type and the decorator solve different problems:
The types help developers understand the data.
The metadata helps Angular understand the class.
Together, they create a more predictable application.
TypeScript becomes more valuable as the project grows
For a small script, TypeScript may feel like unnecessary ceremony.
For a large application, it becomes a safety system.
Suppose a backend response changes from this:
interface User {
id: string;
name: string;
}to this:
interface User {
id: string;
fullName: string;
}Once the type is updated, TypeScript can identify the places that still use user.name.
Without that contract, you may discover those broken usages only after opening the affected screens.
This is why TypeScript is especially valuable for:

• Large development teams

• Long-lived applications

• Shared component libraries

• Complex business domains

• Frequently changing APIs

• Applications that require regular refactoring
TypeScript does not eliminate bugs.
It moves many bugs from runtime to development time, where they are cheaper to fix.
The danger of any
One of the most common TypeScript mistakes is using any whenever the compiler reports a problem.
function displayUser(user: any) {
return user.nmae;
}The typo in name is no longer detected.
any does not solve the type problem.
It tells TypeScript to stop checking that value.
There are valid situations where any may temporarily be necessary, especially while migrating older code or working with an untyped library.
But using it casually removes the protection TypeScript was introduced to provide.
When the value is genuinely unknown, unknown is usually safer because TypeScript forces you to inspect or narrow it before use.
Better types can model real UI states
TypeScript becomes even more useful when it models the actual states of an application.
A common approach looks like this:
interface LoadState<T> {
loading?: boolean;
data?: T;
error?: string;
}But this allows impossible combinations:
{
loading: true,
data: user,
error: 'Request failed'
}A discriminated union expresses the states more accurately:
type LoadState<T> =
| { status: 'loading' }
| { status: 'success'; data: T }
| { status: 'error'; message: string };Now TypeScript understands which properties are available in each state:
function renderUser(state: LoadState<User>): string {
switch (state.status) {
case 'loading':
return 'Loading...'; case 'success':
return state.data.name; case 'error':
return state.message;
}
}This is more than autocomplete.
It is application modelling.
And because frontend applications constantly represent loading, success, empty, and error states, this kind of modelling becomes especially useful in Angular.
Why Angular feels more structured
Angular is often described as opinionated.
That structure is intentional.
Components are clearly defined.
Services have explicit dependencies.
Templates are connected to component classes.
Inputs and outputs define component APIs.
The compiler understands much of the application before it runs.
This can feel heavier when building something very small.
But as the application grows, the same structure makes the codebase easier to navigate, refactor, and maintain.
Angular traded some initial simplicity for long-term predictability.
TypeScript made that trade possible.
The key takeaway
TypeScript types disappear before runtime.
They do not automatically validate API responses.
They do not exist as JavaScript objects in the browser.
And they do not guarantee that your application will never fail.
But their value appears before runtime:
While developers are designing the application.
While teams are collaborating.
While code is being refactored.
While templates and classes are being analysed.
While mistakes are still inexpensive to fix.
Angular did not choose TypeScript only because it catches spelling errors.
Angular chose TypeScript because it wanted a framework that was structured, analysable, scalable, and suitable for large applications.
The browser still runs JavaScript.
But TypeScript shapes the Angular application long before the browser sees it.
The types disappear. Their influence does not.
